00:15:52.759 --> 00:15:56.669
Another group is building
state of the art sensors and

00:15:56.669 --> 00:15:58.969
writing software never ends.

00:16:00.059 --> 00:16:01.119
&gt;&gt; What's left to do.

00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:06.629
&gt;&gt; Whittaker commands an army of 100 or
more with a $3 million war chest.

00:16:06.629 --> 00:16:09.669
He's determined to have two
robots at the starting line, and

00:16:09.669 --> 00:16:12.019
one in the winner's circle.

00:16:12.019 --> 00:16:14.210
&gt;&gt; A lot of people work hard.

00:16:14.210 --> 00:16:16.000
Red team's no exception on that front.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.019
Winning a race isn't about working hard.

00:16:19.019 --> 00:16:22.069
Yeah, you gotta do that,
but it's a lot more.

00:16:23.429 --> 00:16:26.739
If you haven't done everything,
you haven't done a thing.

00:16:26.740 --> 00:16:30.263
[MUSIC]

00:16:30.263 --> 00:16:34.374
Not all teams take Whittaker's all or
nothing approach.

00:16:34.374 --> 00:16:37.397
For the Hall brothers,
the grand challenge is great fun.

00:16:37.397 --> 00:16:39.360
[MUSIC]

00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:43.980
Each day, Bruce and Dave program
their robot as they drive it to work.

00:16:43.980 --> 00:16:48.620
&gt;&gt; We have about a 45 minute drive each
day, and we're tired of driving it.

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:51.700
We'd like to get into our vehicle and
hit the switch and

00:16:51.700 --> 00:16:52.890
have it drive us home, frankly.

00:16:52.889 --> 00:16:57.819
&gt;&gt; The Hall brothers own a company
that owns audio speakers.

00:16:59.769 --> 00:17:02.840
Bruce runs the daily business,
while Dave tinkers in the shop.

00:17:05.358 --> 00:17:07.740
&gt;&gt; Dave was the engineer and

00:17:07.740 --> 00:17:11.630
chief designer behind
a new robot drive system.

00:17:13.410 --> 00:17:17.686
And that enabled us to compete in robot
competitions, such as Battle Bots.

00:17:17.685 --> 00:17:20.558
&gt;&gt; Great, these guys are from
Silicon Valley, and they mean business,

00:17:20.558 --> 00:17:22.223
look at this bad boy, how heavy is that?

00:17:22.223 --> 00:17:23.617
&gt;&gt; 350 pounds.

00:17:23.617 --> 00:17:26.368
&gt;&gt; Drillzilla just has too much power.

00:17:26.368 --> 00:17:29.089
&gt;&gt; He's twice the weight because-
&gt;&gt; We got second place in the world

00:17:29.089 --> 00:17:31.399
championship in Robot Wars.

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:33.198
If you think about fighting robots,

00:17:33.198 --> 00:17:36.853
where you're actually controlling
them through remote control device,

00:17:36.853 --> 00:17:39.885
the next logical step is that for
vehicle that drives itself.

00:17:39.885 --> 00:17:43.112
[MUSIC]

00:17:43.112 --> 00:17:46.590
&gt;&gt; Instead of lasers, the Hall brothers
experimented with video camera.

00:17:47.589 --> 00:17:52.224
Inspired by the way humans see,
the technique is called stereo vision.

00:17:52.224 --> 00:17:55.192
[MUSIC]

00:17:55.192 --> 00:17:59.069
On the roof,
they mounted two cameras side by side.

00:17:59.069 --> 00:18:02.936
By measuring the lateral shift
of specific areas in each image,

00:18:02.936 --> 00:18:05.659
the robot compute
the distance of objects and

00:18:05.660 --> 00:18:08.611
creates a difference map
to avoid hitting them.

00:18:08.611 --> 00:18:11.796
[MUSIC]

00:18:11.796 --> 00:18:12.772
&gt;&gt; Nice.

00:18:12.771 --> 00:18:16.250
[SOUND] [LAUGH] Sweet.

00:18:16.250 --> 00:18:21.733
&gt;&gt; Even after decades of research,
stereo vision is an unproven technology,

00:18:21.733 --> 00:18:25.343
and at higher speeds,
notoriously unreliable.

00:18:25.344 --> 00:18:29.963
&gt;&gt; [NOISE]
[SOUND]

00:18:29.963 --> 00:18:33.198
Sorry.

00:18:33.199 --> 00:18:37.329
&gt;&gt; After a few scares, the Hall
brothers scrapped stereo vision, and

00:18:37.328 --> 00:18:39.876
started building their spinning laser.

00:18:39.876 --> 00:18:41.031
[SOUND]

00:18:41.031 --> 00:18:44.923
[MUSIC]

00:18:44.923 --> 00:18:50.039
In the fields of Iowa, team TerraMax
is a group of defense contractors.

00:18:50.039 --> 00:18:51.259
Like all competitors,

00:18:51.259 --> 00:18:55.529
they're not allowed to use government
money to compete in the Grand Challenge.

00:18:55.529 --> 00:18:58.849
Still, for them, this is no hobby.

00:18:58.849 --> 00:19:04.069
Their vehicle is a big yellow goose
that might lay a giant golden egg.

00:19:04.069 --> 00:19:07.299
TerraMax is a six wheel drive vehicle.

00:19:07.299 --> 00:19:10.819
It is really the logistical
backbone of the Marine Core.

00:19:10.819 --> 00:19:13.839
And we think it's one of the most
mobile vehicles in the world.

00:19:15.309 --> 00:19:20.029
&gt;&gt; Oshkosh has sold more than 6,000
of these trucks to the military.

00:19:20.029 --> 00:19:23.920
With the prowess of an Olympic athlete,
it plunges into water,

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:26.550
charges up hills, and
even takes to the air.

00:19:27.839 --> 00:19:30.774
So it's got the muscle,
but what about the brains?

00:19:30.775 --> 00:19:35.968
[SOUND] Without a driver, TerraMax is

00:19:35.968 --> 00:19:41.670
more of a timid giant
than a raging bull.

00:19:41.670 --> 00:19:43.609
But the team is confident of its future.

00:19:43.608 --> 00:19:46.350
[MUSIC]

00:19:46.351 --> 00:19:50.898
In ten years, the Pentagon plans to
convert one-third of all military

00:19:50.897 --> 00:19:55.919
vehicles to unmanned operation, and
team TerraMax is very eager to help out.

00:19:55.920 --> 00:19:58.562
[BLANK_AUDIO]

00:19:58.561 --> 00:20:00.646
[SOUND]

00:20:00.646 --> 00:20:02.203
[BLANK_AUDIO]

00:20:02.203 --> 00:20:05.549
Making autonomous vehicles
is a tough problem, but

00:20:05.549 --> 00:20:09.124
apparently not tough enough for
Anthony Levandowski,

00:20:09.124 --> 00:20:13.776
who's turning the Grand Challenge
into a two-wheeled balancing act.

00:20:13.776 --> 00:20:17.393
&gt;&gt; A bike can do things that a truck and
a car really can't do.

00:20:17.393 --> 00:20:22.139
[MUSIC]

00:20:22.138 --> 00:20:26.419
You can do really sharp turns,
you can go through a forest,

00:20:26.420 --> 00:20:32.860
really tight spaces, the agility is
just there, it's not on the vehicles.

00:20:32.859 --> 00:20:33.369
Yeah, turn it on.

00:20:34.880 --> 00:20:38.265
&gt;&gt; Anthony dropped out of grad
school at UC Berkeley, and

00:20:38.265 --> 00:20:41.882
spent two years teaching
Ghost Rider to stay up by itself.

00:20:41.882 --> 00:20:44.074
[MUSIC]

00:20:44.074 --> 00:20:46.950
&gt;&gt; We are making a motor
cycle to drive itself.

00:20:46.950 --> 00:20:48.809
Can you get any cooler than that?

00:20:48.809 --> 00:20:51.706
That's why everybody
in the team puts it so

00:20:51.707 --> 00:20:56.624
many hours, because when you see it
works, you say, wow, I made that.

00:20:56.624 --> 00:21:01.790
[MUSIC]

00:21:01.790 --> 00:21:04.631
&gt;&gt; A year earlier at
the first Grand Challenge,

00:21:04.632 --> 00:21:07.230
Ghost Rider made it's world debut.

00:21:07.230 --> 00:21:12.970
&gt;&gt; I haven't slept in two days,
and I'm super excited.

00:21:12.970 --> 00:21:16.827
I mean, this is the culmination
of six months worth of work,

00:21:16.827 --> 00:21:19.259
and I forget to turn on the stability.

00:21:19.259 --> 00:21:22.315
[BLANK_AUDIO]

00:21:22.315 --> 00:21:26.901
And then the second I saw it start to
fall, and last year, I said enough.

00:21:26.901 --> 00:21:27.845
That switch.

00:21:27.845 --> 00:21:31.613
[BLANK_AUDIO]

00:21:31.613 --> 00:21:32.683
That's life.

00:21:32.683 --> 00:21:37.072
Bad things happen, but this will
never ever happen to me ever again.

00:21:37.073 --> 00:21:41.271
[MUSIC]

00:21:41.270 --> 00:21:44.559
The Grand Challenge has basically
taken up all of my life.

00:21:44.559 --> 00:21:48.509
I don't talk to my friends anymore,
I don't have a girlfriend right now.

00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:51.140
I think it's totally worth it though.

00:21:52.589 --> 00:21:55.105
This could be a chance of a lifetime.

00:21:55.105 --> 00:21:57.680
[NOISE]

00:21:57.680 --> 00:22:01.355
[MUSIC]

00:22:01.355 --> 00:22:03.948
&gt;&gt; Stanford University is
a strong competitor, and

00:22:03.948 --> 00:22:07.150
ran the Grand Challenge for
the first time.

00:22:07.150 --> 00:22:10.340
&gt;&gt; I think the team's did
great the first time around,

00:22:10.339 --> 00:22:14.199
and performed very well, but it was
obvious there was some missing link.

00:22:14.200 --> 00:22:16.950
Some missing science to
actually win this race,

00:22:16.950 --> 00:22:20.870
and these are the challenges I live for,
this is why I do what I do.

00:22:22.049 --> 00:22:23.539
&gt;&gt; For almost eight years,

00:22:23.539 --> 00:22:27.539
Sebastian Thrun was Red Whittaker's
colleague at Carnegie Mellon.

00:22:27.539 --> 00:22:29.940
They share a passion for robots.

00:22:29.940 --> 00:22:32.950
But Thrun has little
interest in hardware, and

00:22:32.950 --> 00:22:36.490
convinced Volkswagen to donate
a vehicle with steering, brake, and

00:22:36.490 --> 00:22:39.798
shift actuators that can
be controlled by computer.

00:22:41.450 --> 00:22:44.420
&gt;&gt; The vehicle's name is Stanley,
so Stanley is nothing else but

00:22:44.420 --> 00:22:47.350
Stanford, but
it also gives the vehicle a personality.

00:22:48.559 --> 00:22:53.349
We think of the vehicle more and
more as a intelligent decision maker.

00:22:53.349 --> 00:22:57.609
&gt;&gt; Thrun is a computer scientist with
a deep interest in machine learning, and

00:22:57.609 --> 00:23:00.779
robots with personality
are his specialty.

00:23:00.779 --> 00:23:05.606
His robots assist the elderly, conduct
museum tours, fetch tennis balls,

00:23:05.606 --> 00:23:10.004
and each one embodies Thrun's desire
to create machines that think.

00:23:10.005 --> 00:23:12.207
[MUSIC]

00:23:12.207 --> 00:23:16.660
&gt;&gt; Sebastian Thrun is interested
in the science of robotics.

00:23:16.660 --> 00:23:20.029
In learning about new
techniques that can make,

00:23:21.049 --> 00:23:26.569
robots do fantastically advanced things
ten, 20, even 50 years from now.

00:23:26.569 --> 00:23:29.339
&gt;&gt; I guess he's mounted them vertically,
but we have no data so far, right?

00:23:29.339 --> 00:23:29.769
&gt;&gt; That's correct.

00:23:29.769 --> 00:23:31.569
&gt;&gt; And
we have no software that can do it.

00:23:31.569 --> 00:23:33.694
Okay, so how foolish of us?

00:23:33.694 --> 00:23:36.030
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]
&gt;&gt; Compared to the Red Team,

00:23:36.030 --> 00:23:40.230
Stanford is a small group with
a single focus on software.

00:23:40.230 --> 00:23:41.701
&gt;&gt; The problem is, based on-
&gt;&gt; [CROSSTALK]

00:23:41.701 --> 00:23:42.630
&gt;&gt; There's a good number of teams

00:23:42.630 --> 00:23:44.830
who think the challenge
lies in the hardware.

00:23:44.829 --> 00:23:47.089
And God bless them,
it's great they're doing this,

00:23:47.089 --> 00:23:48.819
and I know there's other challenges.

00:23:50.029 --> 00:23:51.859
We, from the very beginning,

00:23:51.859 --> 00:23:56.129
pursued a very aggressive timeline to
focus almost entirely on software.

00:23:59.160 --> 00:24:02.730
&gt;&gt; Stanford uses the same laser
hardware as the Red Team.

00:24:02.730 --> 00:24:05.460
But they're experimenting
with ways to use software

00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:08.269
to give their robot a greater
role in making decisions.

00:24:08.269 --> 00:24:09.750
About speed and safety.

00:24:11.380 --> 00:24:14.900
&gt;&gt; So in this display,
the white area is safe to drive,

00:24:14.900 --> 00:24:17.820
the red area is unsafe to drive, and
the grey area is you don't know.

00:24:19.049 --> 00:24:22.720
And the robot then just has to steer
itself so that it stays in the middle of

00:24:22.720 --> 00:24:25.600
the road and avoids this red
stuff as much as possible.

00:24:28.940 --> 00:24:33.065
&gt;&gt; To test Stanley's software on
the original racecourse, the team has

00:24:33.065 --> 00:24:36.539
traveled to the Mojave Desert where
the first Grand Challenge began.

00:24:38.390 --> 00:24:42.630
Most of Stanley's computer code has
been written by Mike Montemerlo,

00:24:42.630 --> 00:24:44.670
Red Whitaker's former PhD student.

00:24:44.670 --> 00:24:47.440
&gt;&gt; Give me steering and throttle.

00:24:47.440 --> 00:24:48.150
&gt;&gt; Steering's yours.

00:24:49.490 --> 00:24:49.644
Throttle.

00:24:49.644 --> 00:24:51.941
[BLANK_AUDIO]

00:24:51.941 --> 00:24:52.339
Great.

00:24:54.890 --> 00:24:55.890
&gt;&gt; Let's step to 15 now.

00:24:58.950 --> 00:25:00.231
&gt;&gt; What's the mile marker?

00:25:00.231 --> 00:25:01.046
&gt;&gt; 7.28.

00:25:01.046 --> 00:25:03.519
&gt;&gt; 7.3 is the critical place.

00:25:03.519 --> 00:25:06.089
In fact,
right after this turn over here,

00:25:06.089 --> 00:25:11.549
the red team rode off the road and there
was this final destination in the race.

00:25:11.549 --> 00:25:13.240
That's a very exciting place for us.

00:25:13.240 --> 00:25:15.170
It's in many many ways
a historical place.

00:25:15.170 --> 00:25:18.289
This is the end of
the previous Grand Challenge.

00:25:18.289 --> 00:25:18.950
&gt;&gt; Swerve to the right.

00:25:20.559 --> 00:25:21.779
&gt;&gt; Sorry.

00:25:21.779 --> 00:25:22.889
I be having a problem.

00:25:22.890 --> 00:25:24.560
&gt;&gt; It's the end of the race for us.

00:25:24.559 --> 00:25:24.889
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:25:26.940 --> 00:25:28.110
&gt;&gt; What happened Mike?

00:25:28.109 --> 00:25:33.879
&gt;&gt; It just, the long lasers can't
see their blind in a corner.

00:25:33.880 --> 00:25:38.145
&gt;&gt; It stuck the force of a software bug
which we're currently debugging, so our

00:25:38.144 --> 00:25:42.162
challenge between April now and October
will be to get rid of these bugs.

00:25:42.162 --> 00:25:45.560
[MUSIC]

00:25:45.560 --> 00:25:49.610
&gt;&gt; Unbelievably Stanley Faulter did the
same place that killed the Red Team in

00:25:49.611 --> 00:25:51.440
the first Grand Challenge.

00:25:51.440 --> 00:25:56.410
But is confident about going head to
head against a team he knows well.

00:25:56.410 --> 00:26:00.040
&gt;&gt; The Red Team is
a seasoned competitor, and

00:26:00.039 --> 00:26:02.299
they have a lot of money,
a lot of equipment.

00:26:02.299 --> 00:26:05.889
They have a fantastic team,
they used to be at Carnegie Mellon,

00:26:05.890 --> 00:26:08.900
I know Red very well,
he's an amazing person.

00:26:08.900 --> 00:26:12.820
I wouldn't be surprised if the Red
team and the Stanford team, and

00:26:12.819 --> 00:26:15.847
maybe two of the other teams
were the big teams in the end.

00:26:15.847 --> 00:26:19.367
[SOUND] We will see,
it's a race, it's a true race.

00:26:19.367 --> 00:26:24.341
[NOISE]
&gt;&gt; The Red Team is teaching its

00:26:24.342 --> 00:26:27.099
robot to go fast,
up to 50 miles an hour.

00:26:29.089 --> 00:26:33.089
Software guru, Kevin Peterson,
has been spending long days and

00:26:33.089 --> 00:26:36.419
nights improving Sandstorm's
performance at race pace.

00:26:38.359 --> 00:26:41.929
&gt;&gt; We've been working on Sandstorm for
the last month.

00:26:41.930 --> 00:26:45.279
I just cut sleep out,
you know, it's not that tough.

00:26:45.279 --> 00:26:48.399
[LAUGH] You get three hours of sleep a
day and drink some coffee, you're okay.

00:26:50.789 --> 00:26:52.440
&gt;&gt; As the robot drives,

00:26:52.440 --> 00:26:54.826
it has to constantly update its
picture of the terrain ahead.

00:26:54.826 --> 00:26:59.870
The faster it goes, the faster it
has to update this picture, or

00:26:59.869 --> 00:27:01.519
the terrain just gets on top of it.

00:27:01.519 --> 00:27:07.289
This is easy for humans to do because we
can see out 300, 400, 500 feet ahead.

00:27:07.289 --> 00:27:11.190
But robots have sensors like lasers
that operate at fixed ranges,

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:14.160
60 feet, at most, 150 feet.

00:27:16.009 --> 00:27:17.690
It's like driving through a fog.

00:27:21.619 --> 00:27:24.258
&gt;&gt; Each team must lift
this fog to win the race

00:27:25.407 --> 00:27:27.049
&gt;&gt; The Red Team's secret weapon

00:27:27.049 --> 00:27:30.139
is hidden inside the dome
on Sandstorm's roof,

00:27:30.140 --> 00:27:33.509
where a high powered laser is
mounted on a device called a gimbal.

00:27:35.970 --> 00:27:39.670
&gt;&gt; The gimbal is a motion platform

00:27:39.670 --> 00:27:43.789
that's a little bit
like an animal's neck.

00:27:43.789 --> 00:27:47.865
It can point sensors left,
right, up, down,

00:27:47.865 --> 00:27:56.319
in such a way that the pounding
motion from the vehicle is smoothed.

00:27:56.319 --> 00:27:59.108
[SOUND]
&gt;&gt; Like binoculars,

00:27:59.108 --> 00:28:03.009
this special laser can see
into the far distance.

00:28:03.009 --> 00:28:06.700
By damping vibration the gimbal
gives it a steady gaze.

00:28:06.700 --> 00:28:08.710
And can point it to
follow turns in the road.

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:13.930
[SOUND] The gimbal mounted laser
is unique to the Red Team,

00:28:13.930 --> 00:28:17.421
which has made several from scratch.

00:28:17.421 --> 00:28:21.930
But it's a fancy piece of hardware
that's hard to build and easy to break.

00:28:24.480 --> 00:28:27.349
&gt;&gt; There's been a lot of discussion
whether you want to gimbal your sensors.

00:28:27.349 --> 00:28:29.419
In fact,
we've actually decided against it.

00:28:29.420 --> 00:28:33.070
We decided against it because we
wanted simplicity in the system.

00:28:33.069 --> 00:28:35.906
Every physical system
that moves can break and

00:28:35.906 --> 00:28:38.750
there's a lot of stuff
you can do in software.

00:28:38.750 --> 00:28:41.287
[MUSIC]

00:28:41.287 --> 00:28:45.513
&gt;&gt; The Stanford team is putting its
hopes in a set of off the shelf lasers

00:28:45.512 --> 00:28:48.720
linked through software
to a simple video camera.

00:28:50.950 --> 00:28:54.299
The camera can see all
the way to the horizon.

00:28:54.299 --> 00:28:58.809
The trick is to give Stanley some way to
distinguish the road in the video image.

00:28:58.809 --> 00:29:02.379
&gt;&gt; So this is just one laser you
can see it steer the vehicle.

00:29:02.380 --> 00:29:07.400
&gt;&gt; Stanley's lasers pinpoint smooth
terrain right in front of the vehicle.

00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:12.110
By overlapping the laser and video data,
Stanley can identify the color of

00:29:12.109 --> 00:29:16.009
the smooth area and search for
it in the rest of the video image.

00:29:17.910 --> 00:29:22.560
The area Stanley believes is
safe is now shown in red.

00:29:22.559 --> 00:29:27.539
By matching laser and video data on the
fly, Stanley can adapt to changing road

00:29:27.539 --> 00:29:31.519
conditions and determine safe
driving speeds all by itself.

00:29:33.119 --> 00:29:37.709
&gt;&gt; Making a car really intelligent
requires to give it an ability to adapt.

00:29:37.710 --> 00:29:41.920
It's just like in human life,
we don't enable kids to have a rule for

00:29:41.920 --> 00:29:43.480
every contingency.

00:29:43.480 --> 00:29:46.306
You tell them how to learn from
contingencies and make them smarter, and

00:29:46.306 --> 00:29:47.432
then we trust them to learn.

00:29:47.432 --> 00:29:49.526
[BLANK_AUDIO]

00:29:49.526 --> 00:29:54.519
&gt;&gt; Stanford is the only team using
adaptive vision to achieve race speeds.

00:29:54.519 --> 00:29:58.952
Whether it will work well enough for the
Grand Challenge will soon become clear.

00:29:58.952 --> 00:30:05.037
[BLANK_AUDIO]

00:30:05.037 --> 00:30:07.720
Back at the California speedway,

00:30:07.720 --> 00:30:14.049
after more than a year of fevered
preparations, the Grand Challenge is on.

00:30:14.049 --> 00:30:18.740
Officials from DARPA, the Defense
Advance Research Projects Agency,

00:30:18.740 --> 00:30:21.339
are judging the final runs
of the qualifying event.

